modules.description: This module implements a persistent hash table that maps string keys to string values using disk-based storage. It supports operations to open, close, query, and modify the table, including adding, replacing, removing, and retrieving key-value pairs. Concrete use cases include storing and retrieving configuration data, caching strings to disk, and managing key-value datasets that exceed memory capacity.

This module implements a persistent hash table where keys are strings and values can be any type. It supports creating, opening, and closing a database, as well as adding, replacing, removing, and looking up key-value pairs. Use cases include storing and retrieving configuration data or caching results with string-based keys across program runs.

This module implements a persistent hash table that maps generic keys to generic values using disk-based storage. It supports operations for creating, opening, closing, and iterating over key-value pairs, as well as adding, replacing, removing, and querying individual entries. Concrete use cases include storing and retrieving large datasets that exceed memory limits, maintaining state across program runs, and efficiently managing key-value associations backed by files.

This module implements a persistent hash table that maps arbitrary keys to string values using DBM-style external files. It supports operations for creating, opening, and closing tables, as well as adding, replacing, removing, and querying key-value pairs with strict error handling. Use cases include durable storage of configuration data, caching, or indexing where keys are not limited to string types but values must be strings.

This module implements disk-backed persistent hash tables using DBM, enabling efficient storage and retrieval of key-value pairs across sessions. It provides typed interfaces for combinations of string and polymorphic keys and values, supporting operations like open, close, add, replace, remove, and lookup, with strict error handling and iteration capabilities. Concrete use cases include caching large datasets, persisting application state, and managing key-value mappings that exceed memory limits. Submodules specialize in string-only, string-key, generic-key, and generic-key-with-string-value configurations, offering tailored access patterns for different data types and durability needs.
